It’s proposal season!! That’s right girl-if you’ve been waiting on that ring, GET YO NAILS DONE, becauuuuuse statistically most couples get engaged between Thanksgiving and Valentine's day-the most popular month being December-the most popular day December 24th! (don’t come for me if he doesn’t pop the question LOL)

Tucker asked me to marry him on December 24th, 2017 out in a feedlot corral with my favorite cow-Chocolate in the background. I wouldn’t have had it any other way! It was the best time in our life but also slightly overwhelming because after one day of being engaged all anyone could ask us,“Have you picked a date?”. 

I am going to give you a bit of advice from a past bride AND wedding vendor over the next few weeks!

Part 1: Wedding Planning Timeline

The most popular time to get married (especially in my home state of Colorado) is JUNE and SEPTEMBER. While all months May-November are packed with the hustle and bustle of wedding season, these two months are definitely the most difficult to secure vendors for. My June booked 12 months in advance.

Hold your horses! Don’t be thinking OH CRAP. If you want one of these very popular months I suggest giving yourself at least 12-14 months to find vendors! I am NOT insinuating that it cannot be done to get engaged in December 2022 and married by June 2023-I am just saying it can be very difficult!

**pro tip** before selecting a date and setting it in stone-contact all of your MUST have vendors and see if they even have the date available. I see so many couples book a venue but their other dream vendors are booked!

I do want to say how incredibly thankful I am to all of the couples who have booked me in the past and who have already booked me for 2023 weddings! VERY IMPORTANT, as of today I ONLY HAVE ROOM FOR 3 MORE WEDDINGS/ELOPEMENTS IN 2023. I wish there were enough days in the year and hours in the day to allow me the take on every single one of you! Contact me through my website’s “get in touch” tab. I have no idea if these spots will fill up by the end of the week or if I’ll still have them open 5 months from now, so just ask!

Coming at ya with more advice from a wedding photographer and past bride as we kick off PROPOSAL SEASON!!!

(if you don’t know what I am talking about, scroll back to my post on December 5th)

PART 2: Today I am going to be talking about HOW to choose or at least narrow down a photographer!

I will be the first to tell you, the photography industry is over-saturated. I bet there are well over 200+ wedding photographers alone in my county. That is CRAZY. Needless to say, if you spend 5 minutes on the ole googs, Facebook or Instagram I am sure you could come up with a list of 20+ photogs alone in your area that you really like. 

BUT
A lot of clients make the mistake of price shopping photographers.

Now hold on, I am NOT insinuating that you can’t set a budget for yourself. I am NOT saying that you have to spend an “arm and a leg”....I mean I don’t really want your limbs-please keep those! You can stay within your budget and still follow these guidelines!

#1. You must LOVE your photographer's editing style. Scroll through their website and social medias to see what the color of the sky looks like 99% of the time. Keep in mind that different seasons and different weather situations bring on different lighting scenarios. So you better try and find some images taken in the WORST possible weather and see if you still would LOVE that if your wedding day ends up being super overcast and gray!

#2. You must LOVE your photographer’s shooting style. Again, get to snoopin on their pages. Do they post a lot of candids? Posed shots? Do they shoot zoomed in and up close? Or super wide so you can see a lot more of the background?

#3. You must LOVE their personality. Your photographer is practically the ONLY vendor who will be attached to your hip ALL DAY LONG. My brides usually see my face more on their wedding day than their partners! Make sure who you choose is someone you would actually see yourself enjoying spending time with outside of your wedding. The way they talk, the way they act, are they introverted or extroverted.

#4. Honestly-follow all those rules for ALL YOUR VENDORS.

The wind, the snow, the freezing temperatures all mean more work to keep the cattle safe and comfortable. Yesterday we had an awful blizzard with highways and interstates closed, whiteout conditions and constant 30mph winds for more than 24 hours. It’s miserable out but I know I have to get out to feed my girls.

Cattle are pretty amazing creatures, make sure they have a windbreak, plenty of high protein feed and fresh water-they can withstand a lot of what we can’t as humans. 

One of the reasons I am so passionate about my “365 Days a Year, Ag Never Stops” clothing line is pretty apparent in times like this. As farmers and ranchers we spend almost all day working extra long hours getting ready for Blizzards and some pretty painful hours outside in the Blizzard getting everyone taken care of. But I am so thankful to have the opportunity to take care of cattle because it is such a hard business to be in these days.

If you or someone you know works their tails off in Agriculture-tap to shop my 365 Days a Year hoodie!

Today's high temperatures with a windchill hovered around -28 F. While 98% of the population watched the snow fly and temperatures plumet by 40 degrees in 60 minutes as the artic winds come howling from the north. 2% used every ounce of grit, energy and minute of daylight to prepare the equipment, shelters and livestock for impact.

Bracing for one of the most wicked colds in over a decade water, hay and silage are hauled. Protein tubs are purchased and set out. Cows are bed down.

The rancher puts the life of their livestock above their own. "Dangerous cold" the weather apps say, possible frostbite may occur after 5 minutes. But the cattle must be fed, for if they are not fed, they will not survive. 

At night the snow swirlled and hit with a 30+ mph force behind it but the rancher has a few old good girls under the shed who won't venture out to the hay feeder. "Feels like -48 F" the phone says so the rancher hauls in extra hay for those old girls.

The livestock need to eat twice as much usual and even though hay prices are constantly soring, the ranchers keep on forking.

Tank heaters are on, but the water is still freezing over so the rancher chops ice all day.

Diesel gels up. Trucks won't start. Can't feel their toes...but the rancher keeps at it.

10 or more hours later, the rancher is inside and flips on the news. "It's a great night for chili" the news anchor says, and the rancher agrees, smiles and nods their head.

With this storm the rancher thanks the snowplows and first responders for keeping the roads open. Electric companies for keeping the current flowin. But most of all, they thank all of you for supporting the beef industry!

Back from a little holiday break and coming at you with some more PROPOSAL season tips!! 

One of the most common questions asked by newly engaged couples is, "where do you start when planning a wedding?"

You want an honest answer?

It's different for everyone!! But here are some suggestions from an old pro...

Create a Pinterest Board!
I know, I know. This seems so cliche, but Pinterest is such a good tool for you to get all of your ideas organized or at least see them come together. When I started planning a wedding a Pinterest board helped me see what would clash, what was too much and what didn't really fit once my ideas all came together. Additionally, once you get the board FULL of fun ideas you can even create sub sections in your ONE board and go a step further in your organization if you brain works like that (Dress Ideas, Reception Decor, Florals, Bridemaids, Photos with Groom)

Talk with vendors!
I think it is really important to have converstations with your vendors before booking them. I have already spoken about this in depth more in previous post but it's a good idea to get to know your potential vendors and see what availability they have! 

Book a wedding planner! 
While this option might not be for everyone or in everyone's budget, a planner can be a really good option if the thought of doing all of this overwhelms you! At the end of the day you want to be happy-not stressed! Some brides like to be hands on, and others like to let someone else take the wheel.

The last two years of buying hay has been CRAZY!! Come along to a hay auction with us-this is how we buy all the hay for our cattle!

Colorado-and many other drought states in the west have experienced some of the highest costs of hay ever recorded! Two months ago we were paying $315 per ton, two weeks ago I paid $400 per ton and I was really upset at myself for what I though was a mistake buy. After about three hours at this weeks sale some alfalfa lots were going $415 all the way up to $465 per ton! I about passed out. This is why it is so important to figure your tonnage when buying hay. Don’t just pay $150 per bale on a 3x3. Some 3x3 alfalfa bales weight 588 pounds and some weigh 800 pounds. It makes a BIG difference if you are paying $150 for a 588lbs bale compared to the 800lbs bale!

All areas of the country are different and feed cattle differently. Here my cows and heifers eat 1st-3rd cutting alfalfa, cornstalks and available 22% crude protein lick tubs that contain other vital supplements such as fat, fiber, calcium, zinc, vitamin A D and E. You can also supplement in sorghum and oat hay-however I like to stay away from those feeds because they can be high in nitrates and can cause your cattle to become fatally ill. Just something I don’t feel comfortable messing with-although many producers are very familiar with feeding and rationing those option and it’s a much more cost effective feed option. 

We like to attend an auction when we don’t NEED hay. This means if we set a price per ton we don’t want to exceed-we don’t have to buy hay that day if nothing is a “good deal”. 

I’ll be honest, after most of the 3rd cutting went for upper 300s and low to mid 400s per ton, I really didn’t think we would get anything. After 5-6 hours of bidding on various lots and being out bid, we finally snagged these 800 pound 3x3s for $347/ton which was one of the BEST alfalfa deals of the day. Very proud of us, but man I am praying for a wet spring so we can turn these girls out on grass!

1. Like many farmers and ranchers, selling cattle isn’t our primary/only source of income! We actually use some of the money from our “second jobs” to pay for part of the cattle expenses. Draining accounts in the middle of the summer is just not something I am comfortable with. I would hate for an emergency to come up and we have drained our accounts. Why don’t I use the money from selling calves? Well that money (in our situation) went towards improving corrals, buying fencing materials, shelter materials, leasing a higher quality bull, and paying outrageous fuel prices. Additionally we kept back heifers and added a few more to the herd which we couldn’t have accounted for back in the growing season. 
2. Buying hay can be tricky! Sometimes you can buy bales that probed low on their moisture test but got stacked wrong on the trailer which caused mold. Other times a bale can look really good but when you dig into it-you find cheat grass or find that the alfalfa wasn’t cut soon enough and now the protein is all gone. While I’m ballin on a budget, I’d rather not run the risk of buying ALL my hay in one big swoop for the risk of making a bad call on the hay. 
3. Seasons are unpredictable! Especially in Colorado! This year in particular we had way too much wind in the spring which sandblasted all the grass and dried the soil, leaving a lot of ranchers without much pasture to run. The winter has hit us HARD, we are about the break the record for the most number of days with the most amount of snow on the ground EVER. This means since the summer, our cattle have been eating twice as much as we would have thought without being able to run pastures + a super harsh winter requiring more feed than usual. 
All in all, I would LOVE to save a couple thousand by buying all my hay in the summer but while this operation is still getting off the ground-we just can’t.

Supply ⬇️ = Demand ⬆️

Time for a little bit of ag education!

Ever wonder why farmers and ranchers out west say things like “pray for rain”?

In many areas near the Rocky Mountains and Plains, it’s very common to get less than 10 inches of rain per year.

Without rain, we can’t run out livestock and horses on pasture (because it doesn’t grow and we wouldn’t want to over run it). Without pasture our animals require more farmer grown feed like alfalfa, grass, oat hay and sorghum. All of which require irrigation (where I’m from at least) and when it doesn’t rain, farmers are cut back on the amount of water they can pull from the irrigation ditch because a lot of it has to be stored in reservoirs for cities to use!

So with the drought in many states, here in Colorado, our cow hay prices jumped up to over $400/ton this winter. Last winter I bought hay for $270/ton. Because we can’t run the pastures and urban sprawl is taking up so much of the prime farm land-hay is becoming a scarce commodity.

How to know you've got a good mama...told by a rancher.

You have a good mama if she always knows where you are. She may try and hide you from certain things, but it's to protect you from unknown dangers. No matter where you are, you know she always by your side. 

You know you have a good mama if she is always taking care of you. Making sure you are fed with a warm meal on a cold winter day, even though she is cold and hungry too. She keeps you looking presentable, no matter how many times you try and run through the mud. She never gets tired of making you the best you can be.

You know you have a good mama if she protects you. She will put her head down and stand in the way of anything that wants to hurt you. You know she'll keep you safe and you can always run to her when you are in need.

A mama scarifies her own body to bring you into this world. She'll lose sleep because of you. She'll age quicker because of you. Yes, she bellers at you....but at the end of the day you know you have a good mama because she loves you more than anything. 

One day you'll inherit her gentle soul and spitfire spirit, and she will sit back and think "how lucky am I to have such a good baby".

Chocolate is hands down the best mama cow in the herd and the number one cow in our hearts. She is responsible for so many good things in our lives from bringing me back to agriculture to helping me become a photographer. My mama even picked her out in our feedlot. Here's to my human mama and all my bovine mamas!

ITS OUR WEDDING ANNIVERSARY!!!

We have officially been married for one year now, but we have been together for almost 9 years (with a 5 yearlong engagement might I add!) 

Two weeks after Tucker and I started "talking" (do the kids call it this anymore?) I told him I was going to take a semester off from perusing my degree in animal science. 

We bought our dog Riley Roo after two more weeks.

I slowly just moved all of my stuff into his rental house where he was living at the time. 

My business took off. 

Chocolate refused to give me a heifer calf, year after year after year. 

We bought the corgis.

We got engaged. 

Not even five months later our landlords wanted to sell our rental house and we were homeless. 

Took all of our saved money and bought a fixer upper, our first HOME! 

Chocolate finally gave me a heifer calf.

We lived without a kitchen for 3 months while we renovated the fixer upper from top to bottom. All of our money went to every inch of making that house into our home. 

Finally built a house with land.

7 months later we lost Tucker's Dad.

Started fixing up the ranch that was now passed down to us.

We went through the lowest and hardest time during that year, but we learned that life is too short.

Bought Dixie Jones (border collie pup)

We said I do in the spot where we plan to build our forever home.

The week before our anniversary we thought Tucker might have cancer, had an emergency surgery. 

Two short days before our anniversary we lost one of our corgis.

But every single day I couldn't ask for a better person to go through the highs and lows with. I couldn't imagine living one day without him.

Her newest portrait is now available because let's be honest. I wouldn't be anywhere without her.

Are you even a multi-generational family in agriculture if you don’t have a trusty ole International parked somewhere on the farm? You know the one that your great grandpa brought brand new wayyyy back before you were even born?

My family (the Miller family) owns an International tractor like this. My dad calls it “The 7”. It blows snow out of the feed bunks in the winter and sprays for flies in the summer. That tractor never takes a year off. 

The Folger family has their International 584. I am not sure how long it has been in the family, but I know that there is nothing better to convince your little future farmer to come and take pictures than offering him to ride on the tractor with dad!

From our herd to yours…MERRY CHRISTMAS! 

This is the team behind the photos. My name is Lindsay Miller-Allmer, and my husband is Tucker Allmer. We live in northern Colorado where we run this photography business, western home decor online store, ag news radio network and of course continue our families legacies in agriculture.

Tucker’s family owns a Colorado Centennial Farm that has been in the Allmer family for over 100 years. Tucker and I now run the ranch portion of it and lease the farm ground out to local dry land farmers. 

I am a 5th generation beef producer. I grew up in the cab of a tractor, irrigating corn, forking hay at the cow-calf operation and helping around the family cattle feedlot. 

Tucker and I are super passionate about keeping Colorado agriculture alive and advocate for it as much as possible.

Currently Tucker and I own an Angus cow-calf operation but we also raise a few Belted Galloways as well as have started a herd of registered purebred Scottish Highlands that can be traced all the way back to their lineage in Scotland. 

We have three cow dogs…although only one of them is actually good at working cattle. The other one loves to herd chickens and the corgi likes to sleep lol. 

We honestly just like to be at home with the cows and the dogs!
